Patch Set 4:

It doesn't, that's the problem.

glance-api filters fields with value `None` out and it doesn't send them back to the client. This is the first fix of 2 fixes that will allow the glance-api service to send all fields in the response.

Fields are filtered out in this call[0], which does this[1]

[1] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/schema.py#L48

Patch Set 4:

Thanks Flavio.

I'm trying to understand why eg disk-format is different to 'name'.
Currently it looks like you can set 'name' using the v2 api -- even if it was originally 'null'.

Currently if you create an image without specifying a name and then do a show using the v2 api you get this (which contains no name):

 $ glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-create --disk-format raw --container-format bare
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | Property         | Value                                |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | container_format | bare                                 |
 | created_at       | 2014-12-02T11:05:17Z                 |
 | disk_format      | raw                                  |
 | id               | 2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109 |
 | min_disk         | 0                                    |
 | min_ram          | 0                                    |
 | owner            | f68be3a5c2b14721a9e0ed2fcb750481     |
 | protected        | False                                |
 | status           | queued                               |
 | tags             | []                                   |
 | updated_at       | 2014-12-02T11:05:17Z                 |
 | visibility       | private                              |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+

if you show the image

 $ glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-show 2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | Property         | Value                                |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | container_format | bare                                 |
 | created_at       | 2014-12-02T11:05:17Z                 |
 | disk_format      | raw                                  |
 | id               | 2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109 |
 | min_disk         | 0                                    |
 | min_ram          | 0                                    |
 | owner            | f68be3a5c2b14721a9e0ed2fcb750481     |
 | protected        | False                                |
 | status           | queued                               |
 | tags             | []                                   |
 | updated_at       | 2014-12-02T11:05:17Z                 |
 | visibility       | private                              |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+

this is what goes over the wire (no name):

 {"status": "queued", "tags": [], "container_format": "bare", "created_at": "2014-12-02T11:05:17Z", "disk_format": "raw", "updated_at": "2014-12-02T11:05:17Z",  "visibility": "private", "self": "/v2/images/2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109", "min_disk": 0, "protected": false, "id": "2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109", "file": "/v2/images/2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109/file", "owner": "f68be3a5c2b14721a9e0ed2fcb750481", "min_ram": 0, "schema": "/v2/schemas/image"}

yet it's possible to set the name using the v2 api:

 $ glance --os-image-api-version 2 image-update --name name1 2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | Property         | Value                                |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | container_format | bare                                 |
 | created_at       | 2014-12-02T11:05:17Z                 |
 | disk_format      | raw                                  |
 | id               | 2baf3808-f2f2-4b72-a050-0527bbeb7109 |
 | min_disk         | 0                                    |
 | min_ram          | 0                                    |
 | name             | name1                                |
 | owner            | f68be3a5c2b14721a9e0ed2fcb750481     |
 | protected        | False                                |
 | status           | queued                               |
 | tags             | []                                   |
 | updated_at       | 2014-12-02T11:08:18Z                 |
 | visibility       | private                              |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+

I'm not 100% sure how it works -- do you know? Thanks!

Patch Set 4:

Just to be clear, the problem I'm trying to fix here is on reads not writes. That is, the patch allows fields with value `None` to be valid json schemas (mostly used by the client). The patch that follows it, removes the `None` filter in the schema module and allow those fields to be returned. 

That said, you can set name because it's not a read-only property[0]. However, if you noticed, the field is not returned/shown by the client until you set it. That's because the API is not returning it.

I think we'll need a patch for the client to hide fields that are `None` from the shell (assuming we want to keep hiding them).

[0] https://github.com/openstack/glance/blob/master/glance/api/v2/images.py#L702

Patch Set 4:

> Just to be clear, the problem I'm trying to fix here is on reads not writes. 

You guessed right -- I thought the motivation here was for writes. Thanks for clarifying :-)

I re-read the IRC chat, and I think I've a better idea of where you're coming from now.

But I'm still curious as to why we need to send the disk-format over the network.
Eg in v1 we don't send the disk-format over the wire if it is null.

Could we just do an image.get('disk-format', None) in the relevant bit of nova code to handle this (rather than changing the API)?

Or does warlock make that impossible? Thanks!

Patch Set 4:

That unfortunately makes warlock impossible to use but even if we weren't using warlock, I would advice returning all the fields always to keep responses consistent. It's kind of frustrating for clients to have to check whether a field has been returned or not. Furthermore, it's even more frustrating to have the client choose a sane default value for those fields.

hope it makes sense

Patch Set 5:

> It's kind of frustrating for clients to have to check whether a field has been returned or not.

Agreed. But the v2 server has been out for about two years now.

So I think the client application will need to perform this check anyway.

It could assume that it's running against a version of the glance v2 server which includes disk_format 'None' -- but it would then not work against Havana, Icehouse or Juno glance servers.

I think using .get() will work for both v1 and v2, and will mean that v1 and v2 will continue to be consistent in what they send over the wire for unset variables.
Using .get() is generally more robust.

My .02 cents :-)

Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Based on compatibility I'm going to mark this -1 for now.

I think to encourage adoption of the v2 api that Nova Kilo should be able to work against a Juno (and potentially older) Glance server.

Having Nova use .get() to access image attributes is, I think, required for that.

If this is fixed on the client (ie nova) side I think this server side change may not be warranted.

As always, I'm open to correction :-)

Patch Set 5:

I don't think this change breaks compatibility. It's just allowing those fields to be None *in the schema*. The real incompatible change is Ieaddd8a686cf7361f18cb1ee83b7887cdca22bd6 - which I've blocked myself - because it allows null fields to be returned.

The reason that change is incompatible is not because of Nova but because it will break users that check for the field existence to know if it's been set.

Patch Set 5:

Also, all that said, if we're going to require an API version bump for this, we'd rather do this change in that bump and not here. Lets discuss this a bit more.
